    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1911-02-17T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1911-02-17T00:00:00-05:00" n="80"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d80">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 611.3731/14.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Minister</gloss> to the <gloss
                            type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Habana</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1911-02-17">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 17, 1911</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 637.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Referring to certain suggestions recently made by
                    Señor Sanguily, the Cuban secretary of state, which were mentioned in my
                    dispatches Nos. 589<note n="1" xml:id="d80fn1">Not printed.</note> and 626,<note
                        n="2" xml:id="d80fn2">See article on Sugar, <ref target="#pg_102">p.
                            102</ref>.</note> I have the honor to report that a bill has now been
                    introduced in the Chamber of Representatives to authorize the Executive: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>To request of the Government of the United States of America the
                            amplification of the existing reciprocity treaty between Cuba and the
                            United States,<note n="3" xml:id="d80fn3">Commercial convention,
                                proclaimed Dec. 17, 1903.</note> with a view to obtain greater
                            advantages for tobacco in return for concessions in regard to other
                            American merchandise,</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>To invite the United States to conclude a treaty for the reciprocal
                            protection of trade-marks and patents; and</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>To apply a surcharge upon existing tariff rates of 50 per cent on the
                            products or merchandise of any nation which has not already concluded a
                            reciprocity treaty or which does not within six months after the
                            promulgation of this law make tariff concessions to Cuban manufactured
                            tobacco.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>This bill also contains provisions in regard to special seals by which the
                    identity of Cuban manufactured tobacco can be clearly proven.</p>
                <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">John B. Jackson.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
